INTRODUCTION:

For our project, we will be using a modified version of the UCI Heart Disease dataset. This dataset contains information on patients, including their age, sex, chest pain type, resting blood pressure, serum cholesterol, fasting blood sugar, resting electrocardiographic results, maximum heart rate achieved, exercise-induced angina, ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest, slope of the peak exercise ST segment, number of major vessels colored by fluoroscopy, and thalassemia.

Heart disease is a significant health issue globally, including in Cleveland, where it remains one of the leading causes of death. Predictive modeling can be a powerful tool in identifying individuals at high risk, allowing for timely intervention and potentially saving lives. Therefore, we have taken an interest in predicting the presence of heart disease based on a patient's age and resting heart rate, using the k-nearest neighbors classification algorithm. The data was taken from the Heart disease Data from the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository. The columns are as follows age: age

sex: sex (1 = male, 0 = female)

cp: chest pain type

trestbps: resting blood pressure in mmHg

chol: serum cholestoral in mg/dl

fbs: fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl? (1 = True, 0 = False)

restecg: resting electrocardiographic results

thalach: maximum heart rate achieved

exang: whether exercise induced angina (1 = True, 0 = False)

oldpeak: ST depression induced by exercise, relative to rest

slope: the slope of the peak exercise ST segment (1 = upslope, 2 = flat, 3 = downslope)

ca: number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy

thal: (3 = normal, 6 = fixed defect, 7 = reversable defect)

num: diagnosis of heart disease (1,2,3,4 = presence, 0 = no presence)arrowingum`:

no presence)

Predictive Question:

Can we predict the presence of heart disease in individuals based on their age and resting blood pressure using k-nearest neighbors classification algorithm?

First, I loaded the heart disease dataset from an online source into our R environment. In[29]:
#load dataset
heart_data <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/UBC-DSCI/dsci-100-project_template/main/data/heart_disease/processed.cleveland.data", col_names = FALSE)

#make new column names
colnames(heart_data)=c("age", "sex", "cp", "trestbps", "chol", "fbs", "restecg", 
                    "thalach", "exang", "oldpeak", "slope", "ca", "thal", "num")

#mutate data to correct variable types
tidy_heart_data <- heart_data|>
                  mutate(across(c(age, trestbps, chol, thalach, oldpeak, ca, num), as.integer))|>
                  mutate(across(c(sex, cp, fbs, restecg, exang, slope, thal), as.factor))|>
                  mutate(diagnosis = ifelse(num >0, "Y", "N") )

Performed model training using k-nearest neighbors (KNN) and tuned the model.

In[33]:
set.seed(123)

# Preprocessing recipe
heart_recipe <- recipe(diagnosis ~ age + trestbps, data = heart_data_train) |>
  step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
  step_center(all_predictors())

# K-nearest neighbor model specification with tune() for neighbors
knn_tune <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")
knn_tune

K-Nearest Neighbor Model Specification (classification)

Main Arguments:
  neighbors = tune()
  weight_func = rectangular

Computational engine: kknn

Used cross validation (10 folds) and found the best amount of k-nearest neighbors to optimize correct predictions

In[42]:
set.seed(123)

# Perform 10-fold cross-validation
heart_vfold <- vfold_cv(heart_data_train, v = 10, strata = diagnosis)

# Grid of neighbors values to tune
gridvals <- tibble(neighbors = c(1:100))

# Create workflow and perform tuning
knn_results <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(heart_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_tune) |>
  tune_grid(resamples = heart_vfold, grid = gridvals) |>
  collect_metrics() |>
  filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
  select(neighbors, mean) |>
  arrange(desc(mean))

# Display the top results
head(knn_results)

# Select the best number of neighbors
best_k <- knn_results |>
  slice(1) |>
  pull(neighbors)

# Print the best k value
print(paste("Best k value:", best_k))

Using the best number of neighbors, we trained the final KNN model and evaluated its performance on the test data.

In[43]:
knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = best_k) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")

# Create and fit the workflow with the final KNN model
knn_fit <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(heart_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_spec) |>
  fit(data = heart_data_train)

Found accuracy of predictions when used on test data

In[48]:
heart_data_test <- heart_data_test |>
  mutate(diagnosis = as.factor(diagnosis))

# Predict on the test set
heart_test_predictions <- predict(knn_fit, heart_data_test) |>
  bind_cols(heart_data_test)

# Calculate accuracy
accuracy <- heart_test_predictions |>
  metrics(truth = diagnosis, estimate = .pred_class) |>
  filter(.metric == "accuracy")

Methods:

Data Analysis Approach: We will conduct our data analysis by using various predictor variables such as age, maximum heart rate achieved, cholesterol levels, resting blood pressure, and more. We will determine if these variables are useful for prediction by evaluating their impact on the model's performance.

Using the "num" column as our categorical response variable, I will use "age" and "trestbps" (resting blood pressure) as our predictor factors to determine their impact and ability to predict the presence of heart disease in individuals. I concluded on these predictor factors as I were able to see a relationship between age and resting blood pressure achieved compared to the presence of heart disease while I determined that the other variables had weaker relation. I cleaned the column names, such that they are easily distinguishable and readable. I also converted necessary columns to appropriate data types, allowing the numeric values to be easier to work with in this analysis and in creating graphs. I randomly split the tidied data with 75% for training and 25% for testing. This allows us to train our model on a majority of the data while reserving a portion for testing to evaluate the model's performance. Then I summarized the results to find the mean for each predictor and counted the number of heart diseases.

I created 5 different graphs to aid in analysis:

Histograms: To show the distribution of age and maximum heart rate. Boxplots: To show the spread and central tendency of age and maximum heart rate by the presence of heart disease. Scatter Plots: To show the relationship between age, maximum heart rate, resting blood pressure, cholesterol and the presence of heart disease.

After using these visualizations, I came to the conclusion that I will be using "trestbps" (resting heart rate) and "age" to predict the presence of heart disease in individuals.

Expected outcomes and significance:

What do you expect to find?

We expect to identify key predictors of heart disease, specifically the impact of age and resting blood pressure on the likelihood of having heart disease. We anticipate that older age and higher resting blood pressure will be associated with a higher probability of heart disease. Our KNN model should be able to classify individuals with a reasonable degree of accuracy based on these predictor variables.

What impact could such findings have?

By identifying individuals at higher risk for heart disease, healthcare providers can intervene early with lifestyle modifications, medications, or other treatments to prevent more serious health issues.

What future questions could this lead to?

Do regions other than Cleveland show the same trend? If not, then what is a common factor for all regions and why are the trends different in Cleveland? How can predictive models be integrated into clinical practice to support decision-making by healthcare providers?

Summary of Findings

Our analysis found that the best k value for the k-nearest neighbors (KNN) model was 22. The accuracy of the model on the test set was evaluated, and the confusion matrix provided insights into the model's performance in correctly classifying the presence of heart disease. Though the findings were that the error was too high for the prediction model using resting heart rate and age as predictors so using this model would be highly innacurate. Using other predictors may decrease the error margin but probably not to the point where this model should be used outside of theory. To answer the predictive question, it is possible to predict if heart disease is present in a patient using resting blood pressure and age but not very accurately.

Expected vs Actual findings

Prior to doing the analysis, it was expected that age and resting blood pressure (trestbps) would be important predictors of heart disease. This expectation is supported by well-established medical information, which states that high blood pressure is a known risk factor for heart disease and that cardiovascular risk rises with age. The intention was to create a predictive model that could identify people with and without heart disease using these data.

Furthermore, given its ease of use and efficacy in classification tasks, it was anticipated that the k-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithmwhich bases predictionwhich relies on finding the most similar instances in the training data to make predictions wwould be a good opti due to it's simplicityon. Our expectation was that by adjusting the number of neighbors (k), we could identify aoptimized k value that would make predicting whether heart disease was present in an individual.

The accuracy of the model on the test set was found to be satisfactory at 58%. This indicates that the model generalizes decently to new, unseen data and predict heart disease based on the two selected predictors. Though in this context, predicting heart data, the accuracy is unacceptable and should never be used in a practical setting. The analysis focused only on age and resting blood pressure. While these variables are significant, it was found that including additional variables (like cholesterol levels, maximum heart rate achieved, etc.) could potentially improve the model's accuracy. This was an area identified for further investigation.al

Impact of Findings

Having a classification system for heart disease could help doctors diagnose patients more quickly and accurately, leading to earliertreatment. Given that they already have an idea of what the diagnosis might be, it might also save medical professionals time. Consequently, they could maximize the effectiveness of the medical system by spending more time with patients who have a valid diagnosis and less time with those who have a false one. A high degree of diagnostic accuracy is necessary since a mistaken diagnosis has the potential to be lethal. Due to this classifiers accuracy, It is highly advised to visit a professional to help confirm the diagnosis since it is not perfectly accurate.
